<paragraph blockId="19.[151,980,1478,1504]" box="[151,980,1478,1504]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<heading box="[151,980,1478,1504]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" reason="3">
<taxonomicName authority="(Agardh) Trevisan ex Gomont" authorityName="Gomont" baseAuthorityName="Agardh" box="[151,825,1478,1504]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Oscillatoriaceae" genus="Phormidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="species" species="autumnale">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,825,1478,1504]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,441,1478,1504]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Phormidium autumnale</emphasis>
(Agardh) Trevisan ex Gomont
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[840,973,1478,1504]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,244,1724,1745]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,187,1699]" captionTargetId="figure-196@20.[151,1436,187,1699]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Phormidium autumnale (Agardh) Trevisan ex Gomont (photographed from culture LCR-OSC3). A–P light micrographs, Q transmission electron micrograph. A–G. Terminal region of trichomes, showing distinct tapering, variation in shape from strain to curved or S-shaped, and presence of calyptra (indicated by arrow in A). H. Cylindrical region of trichome; division planes of cells that are currently dividing are indicated by arrows. I. Trichomes may be closely appressed, but do not share a sheath. J. Trichomes are usually slightly curved rather than straight as in H. K. Recently fragmented trichomes have rounded terminal cells. L. Cells within trichomes may vary in width. M. Trichome fragmentation in a region of cells with equal width. N. Fragmentation in a region of cells with varying width. O. Release of hormogone as a result of necridic cell formation (nc). P. Hormogone development is isopolar. Q. Cell in transverse section showing sheath (s) and peripheral thylakoids (tm), that have an irregular orientation in the cytoplasm. Scales: 10 µm in B (use in A–P), 1 µm in Q." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776703/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 8A–Q</figureCitation>
)
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1556,2007]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Trichomes uniseriate, cells (4–) 
<quantity box="[523,615,1556,1582]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5–6 µm</quantity>
wide, 
<quantity box="[695,787,1556,1582]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="5.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="3.0">3–7 µm</quantity>
long, shorter than wide to approximately isodiametric, constricted at transverse walls, bright blue-green. Motile by slow gliding. Trichomes straight to slightly curved, except at terminus, where first 5–18 cells are tapered (down to 
<quantity box="[1019,1113,1633,1659]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4 µm</quantity>
wide), straight to strongly curved or S-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[399,538,1672,1698]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,244,1724,1745]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,187,1699]" captionTargetId="figure-196@20.[151,1436,187,1699]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Phormidium autumnale (Agardh) Trevisan ex Gomont (photographed from culture LCR-OSC3). A–P light micrographs, Q transmission electron micrograph. A–G. Terminal region of trichomes, showing distinct tapering, variation in shape from strain to curved or S-shaped, and presence of calyptra (indicated by arrow in A). H. Cylindrical region of trichome; division planes of cells that are currently dividing are indicated by arrows. I. Trichomes may be closely appressed, but do not share a sheath. J. Trichomes are usually slightly curved rather than straight as in H. K. Recently fragmented trichomes have rounded terminal cells. L. Cells within trichomes may vary in width. M. Trichome fragmentation in a region of cells with equal width. N. Fragmentation in a region of cells with varying width. O. Release of hormogone as a result of necridic cell formation (nc). P. Hormogone development is isopolar. Q. Cell in transverse section showing sheath (s) and peripheral thylakoids (tm), that have an irregular orientation in the cytoplasm. Scales: 10 µm in B (use in A–P), 1 µm in Q." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776703/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 8A–G</figureCitation>
). Terminal cell rounded, with prominent rounded calyptra. Sheath thin and translucent. Branching absent. Trichome reproduction through fragmentation into hormogonia, sometimes at regions of variable trichome width (
<figureCitation box="[571,712,1749,1775]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,244,1724,1745]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,187,1699]" captionTargetId="figure-196@20.[151,1436,187,1699]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Phormidium autumnale (Agardh) Trevisan ex Gomont (photographed from culture LCR-OSC3). A–P light micrographs, Q transmission electron micrograph. A–G. Terminal region of trichomes, showing distinct tapering, variation in shape from strain to curved or S-shaped, and presence of calyptra (indicated by arrow in A). H. Cylindrical region of trichome; division planes of cells that are currently dividing are indicated by arrows. I. Trichomes may be closely appressed, but do not share a sheath. J. Trichomes are usually slightly curved rather than straight as in H. K. Recently fragmented trichomes have rounded terminal cells. L. Cells within trichomes may vary in width. M. Trichome fragmentation in a region of cells with equal width. N. Fragmentation in a region of cells with varying width. O. Release of hormogone as a result of necridic cell formation (nc). P. Hormogone development is isopolar. Q. Cell in transverse section showing sheath (s) and peripheral thylakoids (tm), that have an irregular orientation in the cytoplasm. Scales: 10 µm in B (use in A–P), 1 µm in Q." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776703/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 8M–O</figureCitation>
). Thylakoids peripheral but irregularly arranged (
<figureCitation box="[1291,1386,1749,1775]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,244,1724,1745]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,187,1699]" captionTargetId="figure-196@20.[151,1436,187,1699]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Phormidium autumnale (Agardh) Trevisan ex Gomont (photographed from culture LCR-OSC3). A–P light micrographs, Q transmission electron micrograph. A–G. Terminal region of trichomes, showing distinct tapering, variation in shape from strain to curved or S-shaped, and presence of calyptra (indicated by arrow in A). H. Cylindrical region of trichome; division planes of cells that are currently dividing are indicated by arrows. I. Trichomes may be closely appressed, but do not share a sheath. J. Trichomes are usually slightly curved rather than straight as in H. K. Recently fragmented trichomes have rounded terminal cells. L. Cells within trichomes may vary in width. M. Trichome fragmentation in a region of cells with equal width. N. Fragmentation in a region of cells with varying width. O. Release of hormogone as a result of necridic cell formation (nc). P. Hormogone development is isopolar. Q. Cell in transverse section showing sheath (s) and peripheral thylakoids (tm), that have an irregular orientation in the cytoplasm. Scales: 10 µm in B (use in A–P), 1 µm in Q." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776703/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 8Q</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[198,1184,1787,1814]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1556,2007]" box="[198,1184,1787,1814]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,333,1787,1813]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Habitat:—</emphasis>
Alpine herbfield soil, 
<quantity box="[590,681,1788,1814]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.64" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="m" value="1640.0">1640 m</quantity>
, associated with scattered 
<taxonomicName box="[992,1184,1788,1814]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Chionochloa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[992,1144,1788,1813]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Chionochloa</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1556,2007]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,390,1826,1852]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Distribution:—</emphasis>
The species is reported world-wide (
<bibRefCitation author="Komarek, J. &amp; Anagnostidis, K." box="[849,1242,1827,1853]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" refId="ref8833" refString="Komarek, J. &amp; Anagnostidis, K. (2005) Cyanoprokaryota 2. Teil: Oscillatoriales. In: Budel, B., Gartner, G., Krienitz, L. &amp; Schagerl, M. (Eds), Susswasserflora von Mitteleuropa 19 / 2. Elsevier, Munich, 759 pp." type="book" year="2005">Komárek &amp; Anagnostidis 2005</bibRefCitation>
); another strain found in the Hutt River, 
<collectingRegion box="[438,652,1865,1891]" country="New Zealand" name="Wellington" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Wellington region</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[664,824,1865,1891]" name="New Zealand" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
, is likely identical to our strain (see below).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1556,2007]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,403,1903,1929]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Observations:—</emphasis>
Our observations agree well with the strict concept (
<bibRefCitation author="Komarek, J. &amp; Anagnostidis, K." box="[1022,1395,1904,1930]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" refId="ref8833" refString="Komarek, J. &amp; Anagnostidis, K. (2005) Cyanoprokaryota 2. Teil: Oscillatoriales. In: Budel, B., Gartner, G., Krienitz, L. &amp; Schagerl, M. (Eds), Susswasserflora von Mitteleuropa 19 / 2. Elsevier, Munich, 759 pp." type="book" year="2005">Komárek &amp; Anagnostidis 2005</bibRefCitation>
) of this very widely reported species. Some minor differences are that our material has not been observed to rotate or oscillate while gliding, and is more often curved, especially in the attenuated region at the terminus.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776703" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4776703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776703/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" startId="20.[151,244,1724,1745]" targetBox="[151,1436,187,1699]" targetPageId="20">
